Probably beat me.
[Chuckles]

452
00:42:23,958 --> 00:42:25,698
What would you say?

453
00:42:27,920 --> 00:42:30,127
"Better luck next time."

454
00:42:30,214 --> 00:42:31,875
[Turn Signal Clicking]

455
00:42:32,008 --> 00:42:34,044
- Really?
- No, no. [Chuckles]

456
00:42:34,135 --> 00:42:35,591
No, I mean...

457
00:42:35,678 --> 00:42:38,169
I'm sure I'd be speechless.

458
00:42:44,604 --> 00:42:47,266
Up at the corner here is good.
Right here, and then you can just...

459
00:42:47,356 --> 00:42:49,017
No, I'll take you to your house.
Is this it?

460
00:42:49,108 --> 00:42:51,599
Yeah, okay. Right. Turn.

461
00:42:55,990 --> 00:42:58,982
- Yeah, just to the side behind tha van.
- Okay.

462
00:43:00,161 --> 00:43:01,651
[Seat Belt Unfastens]

463
00:43:04,373 --> 00:43:06,364
- All right. So I'll see you next week.
- Yeah.

464
00:43:06,501 --> 00:43:08,992
- Thanks for the lift.
- Sure.

465
00:43:09,087 --> 00:43:11,248
Oh, um, you know...

466
00:43:11,339 --> 00:43:14,001
I'm sorry. My memory's not
what it used to be. I forgot your name.

467
00:43:16,594 --> 00:43:19,006
I don't think I ever told you.

468
00:43:19,097 --> 00:43:21,179
Really?

469
00:43:21,265 --> 00:43:24,723
That's not very polite of me.
So, it's...

470
00:43:26,562 --> 00:43:28,052
Rhoda.

471
00:43:30,691 --> 00:43:32,522
Rhoda. All right.

472
00:43:34,320 --> 00:43:36,652
Good night, Rhoda.
I'll see you next week.

473
00:43:38,157 --> 00:43:39,613
Good night.

474
00:43:39,700 --> 00:43:41,486
[Door Closes]

475
00:44:14,527 --> 00:44:16,392
Listen to me.

476
00:44:16,487 --> 00:44:19,069
Keep your mind clear.

477
00:44:19,157 --> 00:44:21,239
And that's it.

478
00:44:21,325 --> 00:44:24,112
You will have peace of mind.

479
00:44:24,203 --> 00:44:26,945
My dear, don't worry.

480
00:44:27,039 --> 00:44:29,951
Learn to adjust yourself.

481
00:44:35,339 --> 00:44:37,796
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>The distance is not inordinately great.</i>

482
00:44:37,884 --> 00:44:40,751
<i>But one of the challenges you have...</i>

483
00:44:40,845 --> 00:44:43,006
<i>on interplanetary travel...</i>
[No Audible Dialogue]

484
00:44:43,097 --> 00:44:45,634
<i>Is prolonged weightless conditions.</i>

485
00:44:45,725 --> 00:44:47,590
<i>You're in zero "G."</i>

486
00:44:47,685 --> 00:44:51,894
<i>There is a possibility of</i>
<i>cosmic rays coming from stars,</i>

487
00:44:51,981 --> 00:44:54,097
<i>and that could be</i>
<i>dangerous to them.</i>

488
00:44:54,192 --> 00:44:55,557
<i>But once there,</i>

489
00:44:55,651 --> 00:44:58,734
<i>you have no idea</i>
<i>what you're about to encounter.</i>

490
00:44:58,821 --> 00:45:03,030
<i>What really are the beings</i>
<i>on this other planet like?</i>

491
00:45:15,922 --> 00:45:18,208
[Scrubbing]

492
00:45:18,299 --> 00:45:21,462
[Hammering]

493
00:45:23,679 --> 00:45:25,635
[Hammering Continues]

494
00:45:38,194 --> 00:45:39,730
What happened?

495
00:45:40,863 --> 00:45:42,819
I tried to do too much.

496
00:45:50,331 --> 00:45:51,741
Thanks.

497
00:45:56,337 --> 00:45:58,419
You know that story
of the Russian cosmonaut?

498
00:46:00,007 --> 00:46:01,497
Mm-mmm.

499
00:46:05,179 --> 00:46:06,464
Thanks.

500
00:46:08,641 --> 00:46:11,223
- So, the cosmonaut.
- Mm-hmm.

501
00:46:11,310 --> 00:46:14,848
He's the first man ever
to go into space.

502
00:46:14,939 --> 00:46:17,146
Right? The Russians
beat the Americans.

503
00:46:17,233 --> 00:46:18,439
Mm-hmm.

504
00:46:18,526 --> 00:46:21,108
So he goes up
in this big spaceship,

505
00:46:21,195 --> 00:46:24,312
but the only habitable
part of it's very small.

506
00:46:25,283 --> 00:46:27,399
So the cosmonaut's in there,

507
00:46:27,493 --> 00:46:29,609
and he's got this portal window,

508
00:46:29,704 --> 00:46:34,448
and he's looking out of it, and he
sees the curvature of the Earth...

509
00:46:34,542 --> 00:46:36,453
for the first time.

510
00:46:36,544 --> 00:46:40,753
I mean, the first man to ever
look at the planet he's from.

511
00:46:42,258 --> 00:46:45,500
And he's lost
in that moment.

512
00:46:45,594 --> 00:46:50,509
And all of a sudden
this strange ticking...

513
00:46:51,225 --> 00:46:53,716
[Tapping]

514
00:46:55,229 --> 00:46:56,810
Begins coming out
of the dashboard.

515
00:46:56,939 --> 00:46:59,476
- Okay. Yeah.
- [Chuckles]

516
00:46:59,567 --> 00:47:03,310
Rips out the control panel, right?
Takes out his tools.

517
00:47:03,404 --> 00:47:06,862
Trying to find the sound,
trying to stop the sound.

518
00:47:06,949 --> 00:47:09,986
But he can't find it.
He can't stop it. It keeps going.

519
00:47:10,077 --> 00:47:11,908
[Tapping Continues]

520
00:47:14,123 --> 00:47:16,660
Few hours into this,

521
00:47:16,751 --> 00:47:18,537
begins to feel like torture.

522
00:47:18,627 --> 00:47:22,415
A few days go by
with this sound,

523
00:47:22,506 --> 00:47:28,342
and he knows that
this small sound...

524
00:47:28,429 --> 00:47:30,340
will break him.

525
00:47:30,431 --> 00:47:32,763
He'll lose his mind.

526
00:47:32,850 --> 00:47:36,718
What's he gonna do?
He's up in space,

527
00:47:36,812 --> 00:47:39,178
alone, in a space closet.

528
00:47:39,273 --> 00:47:42,731
He's got 25 days left to go...

529
00:47:42,818 --> 00:47:45,025
with this sound.

530
00:47:45,112 --> 00:47:47,649
So the cosmonaut decides...

531
00:47:47,740 --> 00:47:49,947
the only way
to save his sanity...

532
00:47:50,951 --> 00:47:54,535
is to fall in love with this sound.

533
00:47:56,415 --> 00:47:58,497
So he closes his eyes...

534
00:48:02,797 --> 00:48:05,789
and he goes into
his imagination,

535
00:48:09,011 --> 00:48:11,502
and then he opens them.

536
00:48:13,641 --> 00:48:15,882
He doesn't hear ticking anymore.

537
00:48:17,353 --> 00:48:18,968
He hears music.

538
00:48:21,941 --> 00:48:24,683
And he spends
the remainder of his time...

539
00:48:25,820 --> 00:48:30,610
sailing through space
in total bliss...

540
00:48:31,742 --> 00:48:33,528
and peace.

541
00:48:46,215 --> 00:48:49,503
Why... are you cleaning houses?

542
00:48:51,554 --> 00:48:53,419
I like to clean.

543
00:48:53,556 --> 00:48:56,889
- Nobody likes to clean.
- [Chuckles]

544
00:48:56,976 --> 00:49:01,390
Some people build houses,
some people decorate them,

545
00:49:01,480 --> 00:49:03,721
some people clean them.

546
00:49:07,570 --> 00:49:10,528
How old are you?
Did you go to college?

547
00:49:12,074 --> 00:49:13,780
No.

548
00:49:14,952 --> 00:49:16,908
I read.

549
00:49:19,248 --> 00:49:20,738
A wise choice.

550
00:49:22,376 --> 00:49:25,709
I was a college professor.
You learn more doing it by yourself.

551
00:49:32,761 --> 00:49:34,968
[Sighs]

552
00:49:38,392 --> 00:49:41,134
Did you hear about
that contest?

553
00:49:41,228 --> 00:49:42,809
Mmm?

554
00:49:42,897 --> 00:49:45,388
- The shuttle to Earth Two?
- Mmm.

555
00:49:46,400 --> 00:49:48,356
I submitted an essay.

556
00:49:53,574 --> 00:49:55,439
You did?

557
00:49:57,411 --> 00:49:59,493
It's silly.
[Chuckles]

558
00:50:03,584 --> 00:50:05,540
You'd go?

559
00:50:10,299 --> 00:50:12,335
Yes.

560
00:50:12,426 --> 00:50:14,382
You don't know what's out there.

561
00:50:17,306 --> 00:50:19,342
That's why I would go.

562
00:50:20,851 --> 00:50:22,933
It's a bad idea.

563
00:50:25,022 --> 00:50:28,606
In Plato's allegory of the cave,
the people living in the cave...

564
00:50:28,692 --> 00:50:30,432
[Insect Buzzing]

565
00:50:34,448 --> 00:50:36,188
All they knew,
what was in the cave,

566
00:50:36,283 --> 00:50:38,399
and one day
one of them gets out...

567
00:50:38,494 --> 00:50:40,860
and goes out and...

568
00:50:40,955 --> 00:50:44,072
sees the real world,
comes back and tells the others.

569
00:50:44,166 --> 00:50:46,532
You know what happened to him?
They beat him up.

570
00:50:49,463 --> 00:50:52,170
They didn't believe it.
"T hat can't be," they said.

571
00:50:55,010 --> 00:50:57,672
I don't think we're ready
to know what's out there.

572
00:50:57,763 --> 00:50:59,219
It's a bad idea.

573
00:50:59,306 --> 00:51:01,171
So you'd rather
stay in the cave?

574
00:51:01,267 --> 00:51:03,053
I mean,
if Galileo had felt that,

575
00:51:03,143 --> 00:51:06,351
we'd still think we're the center of the
universe, that the sun is orbiting us.

576
00:51:06,438 --> 00:51:08,679
I mean... They tried to burn him
at the stake for that.

577
00:51:08,774 --> 00:51:10,935
Yeah, maybe they should have.

578
00:51:11,026 --> 00:51:13,233
We still think we're
the center of the universe.

579
00:51:13,320 --> 00:51:14,935
We call ourselves Earth One,
and them Earth Two.

580
00:51:15,030 --> 00:51:17,362
You think they called
themselves Earth Two?

581
00:51:17,491 --> 00:51:19,777
- Probably not.
- Did you wash that?

582
00:51:19,910 --> 00:51:23,573
- Did you wash that sweater?
- Yeah. Yes. I didn't dry it. I...

583
00:51:23,664 --> 00:51:25,655
- I laid it...
- Give me that.

584
00:51:27,334 --> 00:51:29,325
Why did you wash that?

585
00:51:31,255 --> 00:51:34,622
Stop washing things.
Just stop washing things!

586
00:51:34,717 --> 00:51:38,209
Leave them alone! Please!
Just go!

587
00:51:41,473 --> 00:51:44,010
<i>## [Radio: Jazz]</i>

588
00:51:44,810 --> 00:51:46,300
[Channels Switching]

589
00:51:46,395 --> 00:51:50,388
<i>[Man] This isn't a planet with little</i>
<i>green men and blue avatars.</i>

590
00:51:50,482 --> 00:51:52,393
<i>It's essentially a mirror Earth.</i>

591
00:51:52,484 --> 00:51:55,851
<i>If we strike them,</i>
<i>they could strike us.</i>

592
00:51:55,946 --> 00:51:59,279
<i>If we attempt to enslave them,</i>
<i>they could enslave us.</i>

593
00:51:59,366 --> 00:52:02,699
<i>It's the perfect scenario</i>
<i>for mutually assured destruction.</i>

594
00:52:18,636 --> 00:52:20,627
<i>[Woman On TV]</i>
<i>Preparations are nearing completion...</i>

595
00:52:20,721 --> 00:52:23,303
<i>for interplanetary travel</i>
<i>to Earth Two.</i>

596
00:52:23,390 --> 00:52:26,678
<i>The modified</i> Saturn 5 <i>rocket</i>
<i>has undergone rigorous testing...</i>

597
00:52:26,769 --> 00:52:28,930
<i>to meet federal</i>
<i>aerospace guidelines.</i>

598
00:52:29,021 --> 00:52:32,354
<i>Protesters are calling this</i>
<i>a modern-day Tower of Babel.</i>

599
00:52:32,441 --> 00:52:34,648
Where's Purdeep?

600
00:52:34,735 --> 00:52:36,475
Checked out.

601
00:52:36,570 --> 00:52:38,777
When's he coming back?

602
00:52:38,864 --> 00:52:40,525
I don't think he is.

603
00:52:40,616 --> 00:52:42,572
Poured bleach in his ears.

604
00:52:43,243 --> 00:52:44,574
What?

605
00:52:45,496 --> 00:52:47,612
- Yeah.
- [Bell Rings]

606
00:52:48,749 --> 00:52:50,740
Why would he do that?

607
00:52:50,834 --> 00:52:54,122
Look. I don't know.
I mean, why'd he pour bleach in his eyes?

608
00:52:57,758 --> 00:53:00,795
- He blinded himself?
- Yeah.

609
00:53:00,886 --> 00:53:02,797
You didn't know?

610
00:53:04,056 --> 00:53:06,763
He said he was tired
of seeing himself everywhere.

611
00:53:48,642 --> 00:53:50,098
- Hi.
- Hi.

612
00:53:50,185 --> 00:53:54,178
Um, would you mind coming around
to the passenger side?

613
00:53:54,314 --> 00:53:56,930
- Just 'cause there's traffic and...
- Oh.

614
00:54:05,325 --> 00:54:09,659
I tried to reach you at your work, but
they said they had never heard of you.

615
00:54:11,290 --> 00:54:13,326
Um, management
changes there all the time.

616
00:54:13,417 --> 00:54:15,954
Is that why none of my checks
have been cashed?

617
00:54:18,464 --> 00:54:21,581
That's weird. L...
It must've slipped through their books.

618
00:54:21,675 --> 00:54:23,757
I mean,
I've been getting paid, so...

619
00:54:23,844 --> 00:54:25,505
Okay. Well...

620
00:54:25,596 --> 00:54:28,258
Anyway, that's...
[Sighs]

621
00:54:28,348 --> 00:54:31,090
That's not why I'm here.
I wanted to apologize for the other day.

622
00:54:31,226 --> 00:54:33,968
- You know, I just...
- I'm sorry. I shouldn't have been...

623
00:54:34,104 --> 00:54:36,015
...touching things in your room.
- No, it's not...

624
00:54:36,106 --> 00:54:38,518
It's not your fault.
I should not have gotten upset.

625
00:54:39,401 --> 00:54:41,141
I'm sorry.

626
00:54:44,031 --> 00:54:45,817
Can I take you somewhere...

627
00:54:45,908 --> 00:54:47,864
and show...
show you something?

628
00:54:48,827 --> 00:54:50,317
Right now?

629
00:54:50,913 --> 00:54:52,073
Yeah.

630
00:54:52,206 --> 00:54:54,993
- I have to help my mom out, but...
- Please,

631
00:54:55,083 --> 00:54:57,039
come with me?

632
00:55:23,570 --> 00:55:26,186
The best seat in the house
is this row, right here.

633
00:55:26,281 --> 00:55:28,237
Uh, it's the one in the middle.

634
00:55:45,425 --> 00:55:47,211
Okay.

635
00:55:51,348 --> 00:55:52,838
[Clears Throat]

636
00:56:07,531 --> 00:56:10,489
[Quavering Noise]

637
00:56:10,576 --> 00:56:12,658
[Clears Throat]
Just a little out of tune.

638
00:56:16,748 --> 00:56:18,454
[Clears Throat]

639
00:56:21,545 --> 00:56:25,333
[Melodic Quavering]
That's better, huh?

640
00:56:28,510 --> 00:56:30,466
[Breathes Deeply]

641
00:56:38,562 --> 00:56:41,304
## [Melodic Quavering]

642
00:56:48,155 --> 00:56:49,895
## [Continues]

643
00:57:35,827 --> 00:57:37,317
## [Continues]

644
00:58:13,240 --> 00:58:15,151
## [Continues]

645
00:58:22,207 --> 00:58:23,697
## [Ends]

646
01:00:26,081 --> 01:00:28,914
I'd finally got to
a content place in my life.

647
01:00:32,170 --> 01:00:34,877
Our son was five, and my wife
was pregnant with a girl.

648
01:00:38,385 --> 01:00:40,171
And then...

649
01:00:43,098 --> 01:00:44,884
they were killed.

650
01:00:47,310 --> 01:00:49,551
Drunk driver.
A teenager.

651
01:00:51,439 --> 01:00:53,430
I was in a coma.

652
01:00:55,735 --> 01:00:58,067
And I was sleeping
all the time.

653
01:00:59,906 --> 01:01:03,364
And I was so... angry.

654
01:01:03,451 --> 01:01:06,614
So afraid of what I might do to that kid.
You know?

655
01:01:08,748 --> 01:01:11,831
So I made sure my brother got
all the court documents.

656
01:01:13,753 --> 01:01:16,745
The driver was a minor,
so I never found out the name.

657
01:01:18,675 --> 01:01:20,836
Are you still there?

658
01:02:02,761 --> 01:02:05,343
[Vomiting]

659
01:02:43,593 --> 01:02:45,834
He can't hear
or see anything.

660
01:02:47,013 --> 01:02:48,549
Okay.

661
01:02:48,640 --> 01:02:50,551
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

662
01:03:04,489 --> 01:03:06,195
Rhoda.

663
01:03:26,720 --> 01:03:29,587
You are wondering why.

664
01:03:35,061 --> 01:03:36,892
No.

665
01:03:37,897 --> 01:03:39,512
No.

666
01:03:40,233 --> 01:03:41,348
No.

667
01:03:41,443 --> 01:03:43,729
You know why.

668
01:04:32,410 --> 01:04:34,366
[Sobbing]

669
01:04:56,309 --> 01:05:00,097
[Basketball Dribbling,
Whooshing]

670
01:05:06,111 --> 01:05:07,567
Oh, Rhoda.

671
01:05:07,654 --> 01:05:10,145
Yeah, I got some information
you might want to hear.

672
01:05:11,491 --> 01:05:13,857
Shoot a three for it.
[Chuckles]

673
01:05:16,955 --> 01:05:19,162
Okay, okay, okay, okay,
okay, okay. Wait. Wait.

674
01:05:19,249 --> 01:05:21,615
Um, I'll give you a hint.

675
01:05:22,919 --> 01:05:24,910
Do you wanna get high?

676
01:05:26,256 --> 01:05:27,917
With you?

677
01:05:28,007 --> 01:05:29,588
No, no.

678
01:05:29,676 --> 01:05:33,134
Do you want to get high?

679
01:05:41,688 --> 01:05:43,269
They called.

680
01:05:43,356 --> 01:05:45,017
Number's on your door.

681
01:05:46,025 --> 01:05:47,515
Seriously?

682
01:05:48,361 --> 01:05:49,851
Seriously.

683
01:05:58,496 --> 01:06:00,782
- [Chuckles]
- Wait. Hey.

684
01:06:00,874 --> 01:06:02,990
You better write back to me
this time, okay?

685
01:06:18,099 --> 01:06:20,556
[Beeping]

686
01:06:34,574 --> 01:06:36,565
<i>[Line Ringing]</i>

687
01:06:41,748 --> 01:06:44,660
<i>[Woman] United Space Ventures,</i>
<i>Keith Harding's office.</i>

688
01:06:46,002 --> 01:06:49,369
Hello. This is, uh,
Rhoda Williams.

689
01:06:49,464 --> 01:06:52,171
My brother gave me
this number.

690
01:06:52,258 --> 01:06:54,749
<i>Rhoda, yes.</i>
<i>Just a moment.</i>

691
01:07:00,600 --> 01:07:02,511
- <i>[Harding] Rhoda?</i>
- Yes.

692
01:07:02,602 --> 01:07:05,264
<i>Hi. It's Keith Harding.</i>
<i>I got your letter.</i>

693
01:07:06,189 --> 01:07:08,271
<i>I was very moved by it.</i>

694
01:07:09,067 --> 01:07:11,399
<i>You know, when I was 15,</i>

695
01:07:11,486 --> 01:07:14,353
<i>my headmaster said to me</i>...
<i>he said, uh,</i>

696
01:07:14,447 --> 01:07:18,406
<i>"Harding, you'll either go to prison</i>
<i>or be a millionaire."</i>

697
01:07:18,493 --> 01:07:20,779
<i>[Chuckles]</i>
<i>Yeah, well, I'm...</i>

698
01:07:20,870 --> 01:07:23,111
<i>I'm grateful</i>
<i>it was the latter.</i>

699
01:07:23,206 --> 01:07:26,414
<i>But, uh, it's a fine line.</i>

700
01:07:26,501 --> 01:07:28,287
<i>And finer than you would think.</i>

701
01:07:29,837 --> 01:07:31,748
<i>You still want to</i>
<i>go to space, Rhoda?</i>

702
01:07:31,839 --> 01:07:33,249
Do I...

703
01:07:33,758 --> 01:07:35,669
Yes.

704
01:07:35,760 --> 01:07:37,751
<i>Well, you can.</i>

705
01:07:37,845 --> 01:07:39,710
<i>The seat is yours.</i>

706
01:07:40,890 --> 01:07:42,846
<i>Kerry'll be in touch with you</i>
<i>with the details.</i>

707
01:07:44,185 --> 01:07:46,141
<i>I'll see you soon.</i>

708
01:07:49,148 --> 01:07:50,638
[Beeps]

709
01:08:01,995 --> 01:08:03,485
[Horn Honks]

710
01:08:10,336 --> 01:08:12,543
<i>[Man]</i>
<i>Within our lifetimes, we have marveled...</i>

711
01:08:12,630 --> 01:08:17,420
<i>as biologists have managed to look</i>
<i>at ever smaller and smaller things.</i>

712
01:08:17,510 --> 01:08:20,422
<i>And astronomers have looked</i>
<i>further and further...</i>

713
01:08:20,513 --> 01:08:24,301
<i>into the dark night sky,</i>
<i>back in time and out in space.</i>

714
01:08:25,685 --> 01:08:27,892
<i>But maybe</i>
<i>the most mysterious of all...</i>

715
01:08:27,979 --> 01:08:30,391
<i>is neither the small</i>
<i>nor the large.</i>

716
01:08:30,481 --> 01:08:32,517
<i>It's us, up close.</i>

717
01:08:34,277 --> 01:08:36,484
<i>Could we even</i>
<i>recognize ourselves?</i>

718
01:08:36,571 --> 01:08:39,313
<i>And if we did,</i>
<i>would we know ourselves?</i>

719
01:08:40,408 --> 01:08:42,239
<i>What would we say to ourselves?</i>

720
01:08:42,327 --> 01:08:44,943
<i>What would we learn</i>
<i>from ourselves?</i>

721
01:08:45,038 --> 01:08:47,120
<i>What would we really</i>
<i>like to see...</i>

722
01:08:47,206 --> 01:08:50,118
<i>if we could</i>
<i>stand outside ourselves...</i>

723
01:08:50,209 --> 01:08:52,165
<i>and look at us?</i>

724
01:09:30,416 --> 01:09:33,908
## [Piano: Classical]

725
01:09:38,383 --> 01:09:40,419
## [Continues]

726
01:10:47,076 --> 01:10:48,657
## [Ends]

727
01:10:50,455 --> 01:10:52,696
Hi.

728
01:10:52,790 --> 01:10:54,371
A nice surprise.

729
01:10:55,251 --> 01:10:57,367
You're all dressed up.

730
01:10:59,046 --> 01:11:01,913
Do you remember that essay
contest I told you about?

731
01:11:02,008 --> 01:11:04,374
Travel to Earth Two?

732
01:11:04,469 --> 01:11:05,959
Uh-huh.

733
01:11:07,180 --> 01:11:08,545
I won.

734
01:11:10,266 --> 01:11:12,257
[Chuckles]
I'm gonna go to space.

735
01:11:12,351 --> 01:11:14,137
You won. That's great.

736
01:11:16,189 --> 01:11:19,352
That's fantastic.
We have to celebrate. Come here.

737
01:11:19,484 --> 01:11:21,065
- Come on. We have to.
- [Chuckling]

738
01:11:21,152 --> 01:11:23,438
Come here.
We have to celebrate.

739
01:11:23,529 --> 01:11:25,440
First things first...

740
01:11:25,531 --> 01:11:27,988
is to start with a drink.

741
01:11:28,075 --> 01:11:30,942
We have to celebrate.

742
01:11:31,037 --> 01:11:32,948
I can't believe...

743
01:11:33,039 --> 01:11:35,576
How many people...
How many people wrote in?

744
01:11:35,666 --> 01:11:37,156
That is...

745
01:11:41,380 --> 01:11:43,291
I'm so happy for you.

746
01:11:45,092 --> 01:11:48,334
To the coming true
of your most improbable dream.

747
01:11:48,429 --> 01:11:50,169
Congratulations.

748
01:11:55,228 --> 01:11:56,718
[Chuckles]

749
01:11:58,731 --> 01:12:00,722
Next step is a feast.

750
01:12:02,610 --> 01:12:04,396
- I'm gonna cook you a celebration feast.
- Yeah.

751
01:12:04,529 --> 01:12:06,190
- Okay?
- Okay.

752
01:12:06,280 --> 01:12:09,647
Okay, uh, food.
We need food first.

753
01:12:09,742 --> 01:12:11,232
[Chuckles]

754
01:12:15,915 --> 01:12:17,826
[John]
And...

755
01:12:17,917 --> 01:12:20,659
do they know
how prepared you are?

756
01:12:20,753 --> 01:12:24,041
I mean, with the Joan Tallis
costume, for Halloween?

757
01:12:24,131 --> 01:12:26,588
[Rhoda] I will be fully
trained in the Mojave Desert.

758
01:12:26,676 --> 01:12:28,792
[John]
Oh. Well, that's comforting.

759
01:12:29,762 --> 01:12:31,548
They made me sign
this waiver.

760
01:12:31,639 --> 01:12:35,848
Basically every other line of it
says, "If you die, it's your fault."

761
01:12:35,935 --> 01:12:39,268
[Chuckles] And you seem... you
seem totally okay with that.

762
01:12:42,859 --> 01:12:45,100
You know, you'll need
an executor for your will.

763
01:12:45,194 --> 01:12:47,105
Do you have one?

764
01:12:47,196 --> 01:12:49,562
No, but I don't have anything.

765
01:12:50,491 --> 01:12:53,028
Okay, so nothing to no one.

766
01:12:53,119 --> 01:12:56,202
Sounds pretty easy.
I think I could handle that.

767
01:12:56,289 --> 01:12:58,405
Um, burial or cremation?

768
01:13:00,126 --> 01:13:03,289
I think my body would
probably burn up on reentry.

769
01:13:03,379 --> 01:13:05,916
Or be lost in space, so...

770
01:13:06,007 --> 01:13:09,841
Okay. Ashes to ashes,
dust to dust.

771
01:13:14,891 --> 01:13:17,132
We'll have to hold
a memorial service.

772
01:13:18,561 --> 01:13:20,301
Who would you like to attend?

773
01:13:23,649 --> 01:13:25,640
I don't know.

774
01:13:27,695 --> 01:13:29,231
You?

775
01:13:36,662 --> 01:13:38,152
Don't go.

776
01:13:41,000 --> 01:13:42,956
Please don't go.

777
01:13:46,505 --> 01:13:48,666
We're so close
to something here.

778
01:13:56,349 --> 01:13:57,930
We can't.

779
01:13:58,517 --> 01:14:00,428
Why can't we?

780
01:14:02,730 --> 01:14:05,517
- You know that we can't.
- I know that we have.

781
01:14:07,652 --> 01:14:10,064
Stay, please?

782
01:14:39,433 --> 01:14:41,424
Let me tell you a story.

783
01:14:45,064 --> 01:14:48,556
And if, after,
you still want me to stay,

784
01:14:51,404 --> 01:14:53,110
I will stay.

785
01:15:02,915 --> 01:15:04,871
It's about a girl.

786
01:15:08,212 --> 01:15:10,578
At the start, she's...

787
01:15:12,717 --> 01:15:14,298
naive,

788
01:15:16,595 --> 01:15:18,085
reckless.

789
01:15:21,726 --> 01:15:23,967
She does something that is...

790
01:15:26,856 --> 01:15:28,596
unforgivable.

791
01:15:32,153 --> 01:15:36,943
And one day,
she goes to apologize.

792
01:15:38,701 --> 01:15:40,942
But she loses her nerve.

793
01:15:44,206 --> 01:15:45,787
She's weak.

794
01:15:47,168 --> 01:15:49,329
She lies to him.

795
01:15:55,301 --> 01:15:57,041
And then...

796
01:15:59,305 --> 01:16:03,298
she thinks that she might,
in the smallest ways,

797
01:16:04,477 --> 01:16:08,345
be able to make his life
just a little bit better.

798
01:16:10,816 --> 01:16:14,650
And so she wakes up
every day just to do that.

799
01:16:17,448 --> 01:16:20,315
And some days
she thinks it's for him.

800
01:16:20,409 --> 01:16:24,243
Other days, she worries
that it's for herself,

801
01:16:24,330 --> 01:16:27,242
that it was really just a way
to survive what I have done.

802
01:16:28,959 --> 01:16:32,122
But I think that
I do make you happy.

803
01:16:32,213 --> 01:16:33,874
Oh, my God.

804
01:16:33,964 --> 01:16:36,831
I know that
you make me happy.

805
01:16:47,603 --> 01:16:49,139
[No Audible Dialogue]

806
01:16:51,982 --> 01:16:54,348
It was my fault.

807
01:16:59,657 --> 01:17:02,069
I killed your wife and your son.

808
01:17:04,870 --> 01:17:06,861
You better leave.

809
01:17:11,085 --> 01:17:12,791
Get out.

810
01:17:16,340 --> 01:17:18,046
Get out now!

811
01:17:23,264 --> 01:17:25,004
Now!

812
01:17:31,647 --> 01:17:33,262
[Door Closes]

813
01:17:52,418 --> 01:17:55,751
<i>[Woman On TV] The mystery flight member</i>
<i>is 21-year-old Rhoda Williams,</i>

814
01:17:55,838 --> 01:17:58,079
<i>who is rumored to be</i>
<i>an ex-convict.</i>

815
01:17:58,174 --> 01:17:59,960
<i>Her records are off-limit</i>
<i>to the public,</i>

816
01:18:00,050 --> 01:18:03,008
<i>as the alleged crime</i>
<i>occurred when she was under age.</i>

817
01:18:03,095 --> 01:18:06,508
<i>There are reports of offers up to</i>
<i>three million dollars on the Web...</i>

818
01:18:06,599 --> 01:18:08,965
<i>for a ticket</i>
<i>aboard USV's flight.</i>

819
01:18:09,101 --> 01:18:11,763
<i>We're getting word now that she's</i>
<i>arriving at her residence in New Haven,</i>

820
01:18:11,896 --> 01:18:14,057
<i>...where Robert Hughes is standing by.</i>
- Oh. Oh. Can you get...

821
01:18:14,148 --> 01:18:16,184
- <i>[Reporters Chattering]</i>
- <i>[Female Reporter] Right here.</i>

822
01:18:17,610 --> 01:18:19,601
<i>[Male Reporter]</i>
<i>Rhoda, are you going to space?</i>

823
01:18:21,113 --> 01:18:24,025
- <i>Rhoda Williams.</i>
- <i>[Female Reporter] Rhoda.</i>

824
01:18:25,201 --> 01:18:27,613
[Man]
Just one photo.

825
01:18:28,787 --> 01:18:30,869
Rhoda.

826
01:18:30,956 --> 01:18:32,662
You couldn't have told us?

827
01:18:32,791 --> 01:18:35,123
- We had to find out from the media?
- I ju...

828
01:18:35,211 --> 01:18:36,951
I just found out.

829
01:18:37,046 --> 01:18:39,788
I wasn't sure I wanted to go.
I didn't...

830
01:18:39,882 --> 01:18:42,123
Are you going?

831
01:18:43,802 --> 01:18:45,963
I'm gonna go.

832
01:18:46,055 --> 01:18:47,636
Well, now...
now, wait a minute.

833
01:18:47,723 --> 01:18:50,465
I mean, don't you think we... we should
have a discussion about this?

834
01:18:50,559 --> 01:18:52,800
- [Knocking]
- Oh, they're in the backyard now.

835
01:18:54,396 --> 01:18:56,637
Look, Rob...
Rhoda. Rhoda.

836
01:19:24,468 --> 01:19:26,754
<i>[Man On TV] Joining me now</i>
<i>from Washington, D.C.,</i>

837
01:19:26,845 --> 01:19:29,757
<i>astrophysicist</i>
<i>Dr. Richard Berendzen,</i>

838
01:19:29,848 --> 01:19:33,432
<i>the original proponent of this extraordinary</i>
<i>Broken Mirror Theory.</i>

839
01:19:33,519 --> 01:19:36,636
<i>Dr. Berendzen, tell me the significance</i>
<i>of this theory,</i>

840
01:19:36,730 --> 01:19:38,641
<i>why it excites you</i>
<i>and how this changes...</i>

841
01:19:38,732 --> 01:19:42,316
<i>the possibilities of the planet</i>
<i>known as Earth Two.</i>

842
01:19:42,403 --> 01:19:44,894
<i>[Berendzen]</i>
<i>In the grand history of the cosmos,</i>

843
01:19:44,989 --> 01:19:48,322
<i>more than 13,000 million years old,</i>

844
01:19:48,409 --> 01:19:51,196
<i>our Earth is replicated elsewhere.</i>

845
01:19:51,287 --> 01:19:53,528
<i>But maybe there's another way</i>
<i>of seeing this world.</i>

846
01:19:54,832 --> 01:19:58,871
<i>If any small variation arises...</i>

847
01:19:58,961 --> 01:20:01,327
<i>they look this way,</i>
<i>you look that way...</i>

848
01:20:02,464 --> 01:20:05,001
<i>suddenly, maybe everything changes,</i>

849
01:20:05,092 --> 01:20:07,754
<i>and now you begin to wonder,</i>

850
01:20:08,637 --> 01:20:11,049
<i>what else is different?</i>

851
01:20:11,140 --> 01:20:13,631
<i>Or one might say that...</i>

852
01:20:13,726 --> 01:20:16,968
<i>you have an exact mirror image</i>
<i>which suddenly is shattered,</i>

853
01:20:17,062 --> 01:20:19,053
<i>and there's a new reality.</i>

854
01:20:20,149 --> 01:20:23,061
<i>And therein lies the opportunity...</i>

855
01:20:23,736 --> 01:20:25,567
<i>and the mystery.</i>

856
01:20:26,155 --> 01:20:27,861
<i>What else?</i>

857
01:20:27,948 --> 01:20:30,360
<i>What new? What now?</i>

858
01:21:14,661 --> 01:21:16,117
[Knocking]

859
01:21:17,164 --> 01:21:19,280
- [Knocking]
- [John] Stay away!

860
01:21:24,963 --> 01:21:26,749
- [Knocking]
- [John] Get away from me.

861
01:21:26,882 --> 01:21:30,545
- Please let me in. Please. Just...
- Stay... Stay away from me!

862
01:21:30,636 --> 01:21:32,672
- Stay away!
- [Doorknob Rattles]

863
01:21:38,977 --> 01:21:40,467
[Grunts]

864
01:22:07,297 --> 01:22:08,787
John?

865
01:22:43,041 --> 01:22:45,953
- John?
- [John] Stay away from me.

866
01:22:46,044 --> 01:22:47,955
John, please let me in.

867
01:22:48,088 --> 01:22:50,079
- Stay away from me!
- Open the door.

868
01:22:50,215 --> 01:22:52,126
- I'm warning you, stay away from me!
- Please.

869
01:22:52,217 --> 01:22:55,004
I have something I have to explain.
I have to tell you. Please.

870
01:22:55,095 --> 01:22:56,801
Wait.

871
01:22:56,889 --> 01:22:58,720
Okay...
[Gasps]

872
01:23:04,062 --> 01:23:05,552
John.

873
01:23:07,983 --> 01:23:09,143
- Do it.
- [Exhales]

874
01:23:12,112 --> 01:23:15,229
[Coughs, Whimpers]

875
01:23:16,158 --> 01:23:18,069
[Rhoda Gasping]

876
01:24:02,287 --> 01:24:04,824
I heard on TV about a theory.

877
01:24:09,878 --> 01:24:11,459
They think...

878
01:24:12,673 --> 01:24:16,632
that the moment
we first saw the other Earth...

879
01:24:17,803 --> 01:24:21,796
was the moment
our synchronicity was broken.

880
01:24:26,478 --> 01:24:28,764
That was just
over four years ago.

881
01:24:33,610 --> 01:24:35,521
Maybe they're up there.

882
01:24:36,738 --> 01:24:38,694
Maybe not, but...

883
01:24:41,159 --> 01:24:42,945
maybe.

884
01:25:13,567 --> 01:25:15,182
[Door Opens]

885
01:25:17,863 --> 01:25:19,353
[Door Closes]

886
01:25:20,532 --> 01:25:22,443
<i>[Children Chattering In Distance]</i>

887
01:25:30,417 --> 01:25:32,032
[Snaps]

888
01:25:47,893 --> 01:25:49,929
<i>[Woman On TV]</i>
<i>We are just days before the launch...</i>

889
01:25:50,020 --> 01:25:52,056
<i>of the United Space Ventures'</i>
<i>civilian shuttle.</i>

890
01:25:52,147 --> 01:25:54,263
<i>Members of the crew</i>
<i>of this dangerous voyage...</i>

891
01:25:54,358 --> 01:25:57,691
<i>have been training intensely</i>
<i>here at the Mojave Spaceport.</i>

892
01:25:57,778 --> 01:25:59,518
<i>The media blackout</i>
<i>was finally lifted...</i>

893
01:25:59,613 --> 01:26:01,524
<i>with a press conference</i>
<i>early this morning.</i>

894
01:26:01,615 --> 01:26:04,072
<i>I'm feeling privileged,</i>

895
01:26:04,159 --> 01:26:06,320
<i>and,</i>

896
01:26:06,411 --> 01:26:08,367
<i>oddly, I'm proud.</i>

897
01:26:10,290 --> 01:26:13,327
<i>And, of course,</i>
<i>nervous and excited.</i>

898
01:26:13,418 --> 01:26:16,285
<i>[Woman]</i>
<i>The modified</i> Saturn 5 <i>rocket...</i>

899
01:26:16,421 --> 01:26:18,582
- See you, Freddie.
- <i>...has undergone rigorous testing...</i>

900
01:26:30,227 --> 01:26:33,094
<i>## [Saw Quavering Melodically]</i>

